Hi,

A-ha, you mean if I have

A -&gt; B -&gt; C -&gt;D

A-&gt; B&#39; -&gt;C&#39; -&gt;D

Then it won&#39;t let me connect C&#39; to B?

That&#39;s right, but I thought I had a scheme which sorted this, give me 
a while to think it through....

         Ian

At 14:50 02/11/2005, you wrote:
&gt;Ian,
&gt;
&gt;My napkin drawing indicates this technique results in eliminating 
&gt;some valid feedforward network
&gt;configurations.  Isn&#39;t that the case?
&gt;
&gt;
&gt;Jim
&gt;
&gt;
&gt;--- Ian Badcoe &lt;ian_badcoe@...&gt; wrote:
&gt;
&gt; &gt; At 00:01 02/11/2005, you wrote:
&gt; &gt; &gt;Hi,
&gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt;Philip Tucker wrote:
&gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt;In ANJI we have an option to enable/disable recurrent connections.
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt;The way we determine if a connection is &quot;backward&quot; is by checking for
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt;a loop every time we add a new connection.
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt;I&#39;m pretty sure this is the way Ken&#39;s code does it, too.  If you&#39;re
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt;connecting nodes A & B, then start with B and traverse the net to see
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt;if you connect to A.  If you do, disallow the connection.
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt;Thanks, this is an option I&#39;ll keep in mind if I decide to attempt the
&gt; &gt; &gt;Othello comp. Of course this approach will probably start eating CPU
&gt; &gt; &gt;cycles as the genomes become more complex so it&#39;s something I&#39;d prefer
&gt; &gt; &gt;to leave out of the code base in the long term - being somewhat obsessed
&gt; &gt; &gt;with optimisations as I am :)
&gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt;One possible optimisation is to keep a list of a genome&#39;s neurons in the
&gt; &gt; &gt;order that they are connected, so that again we can safely assume that
&gt; &gt; &gt;making a connection between some neurons with some index to some higher
&gt; &gt; &gt;index in the list is OK. Elsewhere though I have code that assumes
&gt; &gt; &gt;neurons are in innovation ID order, as this allows finding of neurons
&gt; &gt; &gt;with a binary search over the list - so probably the solution is to
&gt; &gt; &gt;maintain two lists.
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; Hi,
&gt; &gt;          You might already be thinking this, but one cheap way to do
&gt; &gt; this is to keep a &quot;depth parameter&quot; in each neuron.  Depth is defined
&gt; &gt; as zero in the input layer, and for any other neurone is the highest
&gt; &gt; depth amongst its inputs plus one.  All you need do then is (i) never
&gt; &gt; connect from higher to lower depth (equal is OK) and (ii) scan the
&gt; &gt; neurones recalculating the depth after any connection change.  This
&gt; &gt; is a simple form of dynamic programming....
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt;          Ian
